Foremost among the measures by which he hoped to consolidate his new era, and by ‘human statute purge the gentle weal,⁷ was the law of murder—the lex Cornelia de sicariis et veneficis.

For its provisions this speech of Cicero's is our principa] authority. There are notices also in the lawyers, but in these

it is not always easy to distinguish the original statute from its subsequent modifications.

Sulla had also, as Cicero informs us, embodied in this law a measure of C. Gracchus against judicial corruption on the

part of senatorsl Under this law C. Gracchus had consti- tuted a new quaestio.
